<subSubSection id="ACF97DC1FFFDB82AFCABFB2EBD41F30A" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="372" pageId="16" pageNumber="371" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E45C2E4AFFFDB82AFCABFB2EBD41F30A" blockId="16.[809,1425,1265,1778]" lastBlockId="17.[827,1443,197,311]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="372" pageId="16" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis id="D697F258FFFDB82BFCABFB2EBC4AF73B" box="[809,1316,1265,1287]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="371">
Diagnosis: 
<taxonomicName id="23E355C9FFFDB82BFC40FB2DBC4AF73B" authorityName="Lowe" authorityYear="2010" box="[962,1316,1265,1286]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Odontobuthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="16" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevidigitus">Odontobuthus brevidigitus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
may be separated from other species of the genus by the following combination of characters. Scorpions of medium size, adults 
<quantity id="231B83AFFFFDB82BFB9FFA91BDF9F75E" box="[1053,1175,1357,1379]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.75" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="371" unit="mm" value="57.5" valueMax="65.0" valueMin="50.0">50–65 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation id="7CD832CFFFFDB82BFB2BFA91BC45F75E" box="[1193,1323,1357,1379]" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="29.[163,244,1576,1598]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1536]" captionTargetId="figure-148@29.[323,1283,195,1536]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 16. Odontobuthus. Habitus, dorsal aspect (A, C, E), ventral aspect (B, D). A, B, Odontobuthus brevidigitus, ♂ (ZMFUM 1438). C–E, Odontobuthus odonturus, ♀ (ZMFUM 1439). Scale bars = 10 mm (A, B), 5 mm (C–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6600021" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6600021/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="371">Fig. 16A, B</figureCitation>
). Colour golden yellow. Median ocular tubercle situated in anterior half of carapace, distance from anterior carapace margin, 0.34. Pedipalp chela movable finger short relative to manus (
<collectionCode id="82F2B68FFFFDB82BFBC1FA14BD12F7E0" box="[1091,1148,1480,1501]" pageId="16" pageNumber="371">MFL</collectionCode>
/ 
<collectionCode id="82F2B68FFFFDB82BFB01FA14BDC2F7E0" box="[1155,1196,1480,1501]" country="France" name="Musee de Lectoure" pageId="16" pageNumber="371">ML</collectionCode>
, 1.40–1.75). Median denticle rows of pedipalp chela fixed and movable fingers each comprising 10–12 oblique subrows of denticles. Pectinal tooth count, 29–36 (
<specimenCount id="F2E5E5C3FFFDB82BFB76F9FBBC6AF404" box="[1268,1284,1575,1593]" pageId="16" pageNumber="371" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
) and 20–25 (
<specimenCount id="F2E5E5C3FFFDB82BFCB3F99ABA2EF465" box="[817,832,1606,1624]" pageId="16" pageNumber="371" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
). Ventrosubmedian carinae of metasomal segments II and III each with two or three pairs of prominent tooth-like processes (
<figureCitation id="7CD832CFFFFDB82BFB95F95CBD1BF4A8" box="[1047,1141,1664,1686]" captionStart="Figure 22" captionStartId="35.[163,242,1638,1660]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-101@35.[323,1283,195,1598]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="Figure 22. Odontobuthus. Metasomal segments II and III, lateral aspect. A, Odontobuthus bidentatus ♀ (ZMFUM 2061). B, Odontobuthus brevidigitus ♂ (ZMFUM 1438). C, Odontobuthus doriae ♀ (ZMFUM 2014). D, Odontobuthus odonturus ♀ (ZMFUM 1439).E, Odontobuthus tavighiae ♀ (ZMFUM 2074).F, Odontobuthus tirgari ♂ (ZMFUM 1398).Scale bars = 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6600036" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6600036/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="371">Fig. 22B</figureCitation>
). Metasomal segment IV length to width (L/W), 1.67–1.96. Ventrolateral carinae of metasomal segment 
<collectionCode id="82F2B68FFFFDB82BFBCEF962BD30F4EE" box="[1100,1118,1726,1747]" country="Canada" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13946" name="Royal British Columbia Museum - Herbarium" pageId="16" pageNumber="371" type="Museum">V</collectionCode>
with several prominent spiniform processes; anal arch with three lateral lobes; posteroventral margin of metasomal segment V with two large lobes. Telson small, narrow, length to width (TL/W), 1.86–2.40 and length to height (TL/H), 2.09– 2.40) (
<figureCitation id="7CD832CFFFFCB82AFC00FEFDBA88F30B" box="[898,998,289,311]" captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="33.[163,245,1382,1404]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1342]" captionTargetId="figure-212@33.[323,1283,195,1342]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figure 20. Odontobuthus. Metasomal segment V, lateral aspect. A, Odontobuthus bidentatus ♀ (ZMFUM 2061) B, Odontobuthus brevidigitus ♂ (ZMFUM–1438). C, Odontobuthus doriae ♀ (ZMFUM 2014). D, Odontobuthus odonturus ♀ (ZMFUM 1439). E, Odontobuthus tavighiae ♀ (ZMFUM–2074). F, Odontobuthus tirgari ♂ (ZMFUM 1398). Scale bars = 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6600029" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6600029/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">Figs 20B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="7CD832CFFFFCB82AFC71FEFDBD4EF30B" box="[1011,1056,289,310]" captionStart="Figure 21" captionStartId="34.[145,227,1675,1697]" captionTargetBox="[351,1219,195,1635]" captionTargetId="figure-26@34.[351,1219,195,1635]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Figure 21. Odontobuthus. Metasomal segment V, ventral aspect. A, Odontobuthus bidentatus ♀ (ZMFUM 2061) B, Odontobuthus brevidigitus ♂ (ZMFUM 1438). C, Odontobuthus doriae ♀ (ZMFUM 2014). D, Odontobuthus odonturus ♀ (ZMFUM–1439). E, Odontobuthus tavighiae ♀ (ZMFUM 2074). F, Odontobuthus tirgari ♂ (ZMFUM 1398). Scale bars = 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6600032" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6600032/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">21B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="ACF97DC1FFFCB82AFCB9FEBCBAEAF3EC" pageId="17" pageNumber="372" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="E45C2E4AFFFCB82AFCB9FEBCBAEAF3EC" blockId="17.[827,1442,352,465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">
<emphasis id="D697F258FFFCB82AFCB9FEBCBC71F348" box="[827,1311,352,373]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">
Distribution: 
<taxonomicName id="23E355C9FFFCB82AFC60FEBCBC71F348" authorityName="Lowe" authorityYear="2010" box="[994,1311,352,373]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Odontobuthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="17" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevidigitus">Odontobuthus brevidigitus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is endemic to the Arabian Peninsula and has only been recorded from 
<collectingCountry id="9CF46EDAFFFCB82AFCFFFE41BAA8F38F" box="[893,966,413,434]" name="Oman" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">Oman</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry id="9CF46EDAFFFCB82AFBB5FE41BC24F38E" box="[1079,1354,413,435]" name="United Arab Emirates" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">United Arab Emirates</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="807253BBFFFCB82AFADEFE42BA1AF3EC" author="Lowe G" pageId="17" pageNumber="372" pagination="1 - 22" refId="ref26151" refString="Lowe G. 2010. A new species of Odontobuthus (Scorpiones: Buthidae) from northern Oman. Euscorpius 96: 1 - 22." type="journal article" year="2010">Lowe, 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
